{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568189"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:10:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:10:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19555"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19555"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.02,0.4,0.44,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12325"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97528"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12325"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19555"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80124"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"787"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4957"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29343"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29662"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97528"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with pain and numbness in his toes. He spent the day skiing for eight hours wearing old, ill-fitting ski boots. He has a history of systemic lupus erythematosus treated with prednisolone and mycophenolate. His other medications include calcium and vitamin D supplements. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His toes are white and cold with reduced sensation. There is a clear demarcation between affected and normal tissue.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent transfer to specialised burns unit","Thrombolytic therapy","Application of warm compresses","Rapid rewarming in 37-42\u00b0C water bath","Massage of affected areas"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with frostbite, which occurs when tissue freezes due to prolonged exposure to cold temperatures below freezing point. The white, cold, insensate digits with clear demarcation are classic signs of frostbite as blood is redirected away from the distal sites. His immunocompromised status due to systemic lupus erythematosus and immunosuppressive medications puts him at higher risk for complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid rewarming in 37-42\u00b0C water bath\u003C/strong\u003E remains the gold standard first-line treatment for frostbite, specifically if it can be a whirlpool bath to circulate the water. The temperature must be carefully monitored as temperatures above 42\u00b0C can cause thermal injury. Rewarming should continue until the affected area becomes soft and pliable, and colour and sensation return, and should be over 15 - 60 minutes duration. Given his immunocompromised status, antiseptic should definitely be added to the bath to reduce infection risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent transfer to specialised burns unit\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered after initial rewarming given his immunocompromised status and risk of complications, but it is not the first step. Close monitoring for signs of infection will be essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApplication of warm compresses\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate for treating frostbite as it does not provide the consistent temperature control needed for optimal rewarming. The water bath method allows for more uniform rewarming and better temperature control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMassage of affected areas\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in frostbite as it can cause additional tissue damage. The frozen crystals within the tissue can cause mechanical damage if manipulated before proper rewarming. This is particularly important in an immunocompromised patient where tissue damage could lead to infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombolytic therapy\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered in severe cases of deep frostbite within 24 hours of injury, but it is not the first step in management. The risks of bleeding would need to be carefully weighed given his medication profile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional management includes pain control with NSAIDs (which also help reduce the inflammatory response), fluid resuscitation, tetanus vaccination if required, and elevation of the affected limb to reduce oedema. Given his immunocompromised status, prophylactic antibiotics should be considered and he will require closer follow-up to monitor for signs of infection. Yellow or clear blisters may develop later, and should be left intact, and smoking should be discouraged as it can worsen tissue ischaemia. Treatment is best in the first 24 hours.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rapid rewarming in a water bath at 37-42\u00b0C is the first-line treatment for frostbite.","NSAIDs should be given during rewarming to reduce the inflammatory response.","Avoid dry heat, massage, or rubbing of frostbitten tissue as these can cause further damage.","Immunocompromised patients with frostbite require close monitoring for infection."],"references":["Zaramo TZ, Green JK, Janis JE. Practical Review of the Current Management of Frostbite Injuries. Plast Reconstr Surg Glob Open. 2022.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9592504/","National Health Service. Treatment: Frostbite. National Health Service. 2021. Available at: https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/frostbite/treatment/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80124"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19555"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80124"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-07T15:56:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-07T15:57:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12325"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97528"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags"